args:
What I should teach those kids today?
Maybe a cool way to send calling cards?
Hmm, or maybe how to properly
throw them...
There's plenty more where that came from!
Noooo! Don't treat our dads like that!
Shut the hell up and watch quietly\nunless you kids want the same!
Stop, please... You swore not to lay hands\non our children!
So ya still wanna take responsibility for\ntheir crime? In that case, I've got a\nspecial serving for you too, right here!
Hey, what do you think you're doing?!
Yeah, what the hell?! You gotta have a\nscrew loose if you're beating on people\nwho ain't even resisting!
We... We got stronger because you taught\nus, so we tried to help our dads...
Are you telling me you tried to rumble\nwith your lord's hired goons?!
You friends with these little snots?\nWe're out here collectin' the lord's taxes,\nand they're gettin' in our damn way.

Interferin' with official work is a felony no
matter how old ya are—but I'm a nice guy,
so I allowed the parents to take the
punishment in their place.
Hey, that's ENOUGH! They're kids, man!\nHow much ＂interference＂ could they\npossibly have given you?!
Don't matter how much harm it caused!\nWe gotta set an example whenever\nanybody tries to defy us.
*sniffle* Coach... We got strong,\nbut we still couldn't win...
I know what you're going to say, Luca,\nand don't worry—I haven't forgotten the\nreason why we came to this town.
And I know we're supposed to lie low.\nBut...

But Joker wouldn't hesitate for a second
if he were here, and if I back off now,
I don't deserve to be one of the
Phantom Thieves of Hearts!
Dammit... You're gonna pay for this!\nGonna PAY, you hear me?!
Might wanna work on your ＂I just got my\narmored butt handed to me and now\nI'm fleeing in terror＂ lines, pal.
We need to get these guys somewhere\nsafe so they can rest up!
For a mercy, it seems they'll all live.\nThank you so much for helping our men.
I'm just sorry we didn't come sooner.\nEr, but how are the kids?
They wore themselves out from crying and\nfell asleep—and small wonder, having\nseen their fathers suffer such an ordeal.
I told them they'd gotten stronger.
Aw, you can't beat yourself up about that.\nNobody could've thought they'd try to\nsquare off with a soldier after one lesson.
But it was my duty to notice.\nI should have seen it in their eyes.
Uh, how does that work, exactly?\nThe eye thing, I mean.
It was only a flicker, but they had the will\nof rebellion burning fierce in their gaze.
I've seen countless gazes like that\nuntil now, and I didn't put two and two\ntogether... I'm an idiot!
The important thing isn't whether you can\nor can't do something—it's whether you\nstand tall and resist injustice.
It's the same for me and all my friends.\nOnce we were oppressed by the powerful,\nwe wanted to help folks in the same boat.
We thought having someone like that\naround would give people courage, which\nis why we formed the Phantom Thieves.
I thought those kids were just playing,\nbut they stood up and fought!
And the fact that I didn't notice that proves\nI've still got a long way to go.
Okay, so what are you gonna do?
I mean, sure—they were reckless.\nAnd yeah, maybe you should have\nseen it coming.
You messed up and it didn't work out.\nIs that how you're gonna leave it?
No. No matter how painful a circumstance\nmight be, we always stand and fight!
THAT'S how you really change things!
Then you know what you gotta do.
I have to show them their actions\nhad meaning!
